        <!-- Chapter 1.1 -->
        <article id="ch1-1" class="mb-20 chapter-content">
            <div class="chapter-card rounded-2xl p-8 md:p-12">
                <div class="flex items-center mb-6">
                    <span class="text-6xl font-bold text-slate-700 mr-4">01</span>
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-3xl font-bold serif text-white">Digital Logic & Binary Systems</h3>
                        <p class="text-blue-400">The Language of Computers</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none">
                    <div class="highlight-box rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
                        <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-300">Chapter Overview</h4>
                        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                            Before we can defend digital systems, we must understand how they speak. This chapter explores the fundamental 
                            building blocks of all computing: binary logic, Boolean algebra, and the transistor-level operations that 
                            process every bit of information in your SOC environment.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">1.1.1 The Nature of Information</h4>
                    
                    <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                        At its core, all digital information is an abstraction of physical states. In classical computing, we exploit 
                        the bistable nature of electronic circuits—states that can be either ON or OFF, represented as voltage levels 
                        (typically 0V for logical 0 and 3.3V/5V for logical 1 in TTL logic, though modern systems use much lower voltages).
                    </p>

                    <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                        <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Why Binary? The Physics of Computation</h5>
                        <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                            Binary systems dominate computing not by accident, but by physical necessity. Consider the alternatives:
                        </p>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-300 ml-4">
                            <li><strong>Analog systems</strong> suffer from noise accumulation and signal degradation</li>
                            <li><strong>Ternary logic (base-3)</strong> while theoretically more efficient (log₂(3) ≈ 1.585 bits per trit vs 1 bit per bit), 
                            requires precise voltage discrimination that becomes unreliable at scale</li>
                            <li><strong>Binary</strong> provides maximum noise immunity—any voltage above a threshold is 1, below is 0</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p class="text-slate-300 mt-4">
                            The <strong>Shannon-Hartley theorem</strong> tells us that channel capacity C = B log₂(1 + S/N), where B is bandwidth 
                            and S/N is signal-to-noise ratio. Binary signaling maximizes reliability given physical constraints.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">1.1.2 Boolean Algebra & Logic Gates</h4>
                    
                    <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                        George Boole's 1854 algebraic system, later adapted by Claude Shannon in 1937, provides the mathematical 
                        foundation for digital circuit design. Boolean algebra operates on two values: TRUE (1) and FALSE (0).
                    </p>

                    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Fundamental Operations</h5>
                            <div class="space-y-3 text-sm">
                                <div class="flex justify-between items-center p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <span><strong>AND (·)</strong></span>
                                    <span class="font-mono">A · B = 1 iff A=1 AND B=1</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex justify-between items-center p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <span><strong>OR (+)</strong></span>
                                    <span class="font-mono">A + B = 1 iff A=1 OR B=1</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex justify-between items-center p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <span><strong>NOT (¯)</strong></span>
                                    <span class="font-mono">Ā = 1 iff A=0</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex justify-between items-center p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <span><strong>XOR (⊕)</strong></span>
                                    <span class="font-mono">A ⊕ B = 1 iff A≠B</span>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">De Morgan's Laws</h5>
                            <p class="text-slate-300 text-sm mb-3">Critical for circuit optimization and security analysis:</p>
                            <div class="code-block p-4 rounded text-sm">
                                <p class="text-green-400">¬(A ∧ B) = ¬A ∨ ¬B</p>
                                <p class="text-green-400">¬(A ∨ B) = ¬A ∧ ¬B</p>
                            </div>
                            <p class="text-slate-400 text-xs mt-3">
                                These laws allow us to convert between NAND/NOR universal gate implementations, 
                                crucial for understanding hardware Trojans and side-channel attacks.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">1.1.3 Number Systems & Encoding</h4>

                    <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                        Cybersecurity professionals must fluently convert between number systems, as memory addresses, 
                        network protocols, and cryptographic keys all require precise interpretation.
                    </p>

                    <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
                        <table class="w-full text-sm text-left text-slate-300">
                            <thead class="text-xs text-slate-400 uppercase bg-slate-800">
                                <tr>
                                    <th class="px-6 py-3">Decimal</th>
                                    <th class="px-6 py-3">Binary</th>
                                    <th class="px-6 py-3">Octal</th>
                                    <th class="px-6 py-3">Hexadecimal</th>
                                    <th class="px-6 py-3">Security Relevance</th>
                                </tr>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody class="divide-y divide-slate-700">
                                <tr class="bg-slate-900/50">
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">0</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">0000</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">0</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">0x0</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4">NULL pointer, string terminator</td>
                                </tr>
                                <tr>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">255</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">11111111</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">377</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">0xFF</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4">Max 8-bit value, common in subnet masks</td>
                                </tr>
                                <tr class="bg-slate-900/50">
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">1024</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">10000000000</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">2000</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">0x400</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4">1KB, buffer sizes, memory pages</td>
                                </tr>
                                <tr>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">65535</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">1111111111111111</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">177777</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4 font-mono">0xFFFF</td>
                                    <td class="px-6 py-4">Max 16-bit value, max port number</td>
                                </tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>

                    <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                        <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Two's Complement: Signed Integer Representation</h5>
                        <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                            Modern computers use two's complement to represent signed integers, solving the "negative zero" problem 
                            of sign-magnitude representation and simplifying arithmetic operations.
                        </p>
                        <div class="code-block p-4 rounded mb-4">
                            <p class="text-slate-300">To represent -5 in 8-bit two's complement:</p>
                            <p class="text-green-400 mt-2">1. Start with positive 5: 00000101</p>
                            <p class="text-green-400">2. Invert all bits (one's complement): 11111010</p>
                            <p class="text-green-400">3. Add 1: 11111011</p>
                            <p class="text-blue-400 mt-2">Result: 0xFB = -5</p>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm">
                            <strong>Security Implication:</strong> Integer overflow vulnerabilities occur when arithmetic operations 
                            exceed the representable range. For 32-bit signed integers, adding 1 to 2,147,483,647 (0x7FFFFFFF) 
                            yields -2,147,483,648 (0x80000000), potentially bypassing bounds checks.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">1.1.4 Character Encoding & Unicode</h4>

                    <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                        Text processing is fundamental to security analysis—logs, payloads, and configuration files all require 
                        proper encoding understanding to prevent injection attacks and data corruption.
                    </p>

                    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 my-6">
                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-4">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-2">ASCII (7-bit)</h5>
                            <p class="text-xs text-slate-400 mb-2">American Standard Code for Information Interchange</p>
                            <div class="font-mono text-xs space-y-1">
                                <p>0x41 = 'A'</p>
                                <p>0x30 = '0'</p>
                                <p>0x0A = LF (\n)</p>
                                <p>0x00 = NULL</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-4">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-2">UTF-8 (Variable)</h5>
                            <p class="text-xs text-slate-400 mb-2">Backward-compatible Unicode encoding</p>
                            <div class="font-mono text-xs space-y-1">
                                <p>0x00-0x7F: 1 byte</p>
                                <p>0xC0-0xDF: 2 bytes</p>
                                <p>0xE0-0xEF: 3 bytes</p>
                                <p>0xF0-0xF7: 4 bytes</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-4">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-2">Security Concerns</h5>
                            <ul class="text-xs text-slate-400 space-y-1">
                                <li>• Null byte injection</li>
                                <li>• UTF-8 overlong encodings</li>
                                <li>• Character set mismatches</li>
                                <li>• Homograph attacks</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="highlight-box rounded-xl p-6 mt-8">
                        <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-300">Practical Lab: Binary Analysis</h4>
                        <div class="code-block p-4 rounded">
                            <p class="text-slate-400"># Analyze the binary representation of your network interface MAC address</p>
                            <p class="text-green-400">$ ifconfig eth0 | grep ether | awk '{print $2}'</p>
                            <p class="text-slate-400 mt-2"># Convert to binary to understand the structure:</p>
                            <p class="text-green-400"># AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF</p>
                            <p class="text-green-400"># 10101010:10111011:11001100:11011101:11101110:11111111</p>
                            <p class="text-slate-400 mt-2"># First bit: 0=Unicast, 1=Multicast</p>
                            <p class="text-slate-400"># Second bit: 0=Universal, 1=Locally administered</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
