                    <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                        <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Endianness: Byte Ordering Security Implications</h5>
                        <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                            Endianness determines how multi-byte values are stored in memory. Misunderstanding endianness leads to 
                            protocol parsing vulnerabilities and network byte order confusion.
                        </p>
                        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                            <div class="bg-slate-800 p-4 rounded">
                                <h6 class="font-semibold text-green-400 mb-2">Little-Endian (x86)</h6>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-300">Least significant byte at lowest address</p>
                                <p class="font-mono text-xs mt-2 text-slate-400">0x12345678 → 78 56 34 12</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-slate-800 p-4 rounded">
                                <h6 class="font-semibold text-green-400 mb-2">Big-Endian (Network)</h6>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-300">Most significant byte at lowest address</p>
                                <p class="font-mono text-xs mt-2 text-slate-400">0x12345678 → 12 34 56 78</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm mt-4">
                            <strong>Security Impact:</strong> The infamous <em>network byte order</em> (big-endian) vs. host byte order 
                            confusion has caused countless buffer overflows when length fields are misinterpreted.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">1.2.4 Memory Hierarchy & Caching</h4>

                    <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                        Modern processors employ a complex hierarchy of memory types to balance speed, cost, and capacity. 
