                <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none">
                    <div class="highlight-box rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
                        <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-300">Chapter Overview</h4>
                        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                            Memory management is the cornerstone of operating system security. Understanding virtual memory, 
                            paging, segmentation, and memory protection mechanisms is essential for analyzing exploits, 
                            understanding malware behavior, and implementing secure coding practices.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">1.3.1 Virtual Memory Architecture</h4>

                    <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                        Virtual memory creates an abstraction layer between physical hardware and running processes, providing 
                        isolation, protection, and the illusion of infinite memory. Each process operates in its own virtual 
                        address space, typically 2⁴⁸ bytes (256TB) on modern x86-64 systems, far exceeding physical RAM.
                    </p>

                    <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                        <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">Address Translation Process</h5>
                        <div class="space-y-3 text-sm">
                            <div class="flex items-center space-x-4 p-3 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                <span class="font-mono text-blue-400">Virtual Address</span>
                                <span class="text-slate-500">→</span>
                                <span class="text-slate-300">MMU Translation</span>
                                <span class="text-slate-500">→</span>
                                <span class="font-mono text-green-400">Physical Address</span>
                            </div>
                            <p class="text-slate-400">
                                The Memory Management Unit (MMU) uses page tables to map virtual pages to physical frames. 
                                On x86-64, this involves 4-level paging (soon 5-level with LA57), walking through:
                            </p>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-300 ml-4 space-y-1">
                                <li>PML4 (Page Map Level 4)</li>
                                <li>PDPT (Page Directory Pointer Table)</li>
                                <li>PD (Page Directory)</li>
                                <li>PT (Page Table)</li>
                                <li>Offset (12 bits for 4KB pages)</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">1.3.2 Page Tables & Translation Lookaside Buffer</h4>

                    <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                        Page table walks are expensive (4 memory accesses per translation on x86-64). The Translation Lookaside 
                        Buffer (TLB) caches recent translations, reducing overhead to near-zero for cached entries.
                    </p>

                    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Page Table Entry (PTE) Flags</h5>
                            <div class="space-y-2 text-xs font-mono">
                                <div class="flex justify-between p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <span class="text-green-400">P (Present)</span>
                                    <span class="text-slate-400">Page in physical memory</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex justify-between p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <span class="text-green-400">R/W (Read/Write)</span>
                                    <span class="text-slate-400">Write permission</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex justify-between p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <span class="text-green-400">U/S (User/Supervisor)</span>
                                    <span class="text-slate-400">Ring 3 accessible</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex justify-between p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <span class="text-green-400">NX (No Execute)</span>
                                    <span class="text-slate-400">XD bit (bit 63)</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex justify-between p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <span class="text-green-400">A (Accessed)</span>
                                    <span class="text-slate-400">Page touched</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex justify-between p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <span class="text-green-400">D (Dirty)</span>
                                    <span class="text-slate-400">Page modified</span>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Security Implications</h5>
                            <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-300">
                                <li>• <strong>NX Bit:</strong> Prevents code execution from stack/heap (DEP)</li>
                                <li>• <strong>SMEP:</strong> Supervisor Mode Execution Prevention</li>
                                <li>• <strong>SMAP:</strong> Supervisor Mode Access Prevention</li>
                                <li>• <strong>ASLR:</strong> Randomizes base addresses</li>
                                <li>• <strong>Page Table Isolation:</strong> Meltdown mitigation</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">1.3.3 Memory Protection & Exploitation</h4>

                    <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                        <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">Classic Stack Buffer Overflow</h5>
                        <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                            Understanding memory layout is crucial for both exploitation and defense. Consider the traditional 
