                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.1.1 What is a Network?</h4>

                        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                            A computer network is a collection of autonomous computing devices interconnected for resource 
                            sharing, communication, and coordination. From a security perspective, every connection represents 
                            a potential attack vector, and every shared resource requires access control.
                        </p>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">Network Classification by Scale</h5>
                            <div class="space-y-4">
                                <div class="flex items-start space-x-4 p-4 bg-slate-800 rounded-lg">
                                    <div class="layer-indicator bg-purple-600 text-white text-xs">PAN</div>
                                    <div>
                                        <h6 class="font-semibold text-slate-200">Personal Area Network</h6>
                                        <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">Range: ~10m | Bluetooth, USB, NFC</p>
                                        <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-1">Security: Pairing vulnerabilities, bluejacking, bluesnarfing</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex items-start space-x-4 p-4 bg-slate-800 rounded-lg">
                                    <div class="layer-indicator bg-blue-600 text-white text-xs">LAN</div>
                                    <div>
                                        <h6 class="font-semibold text-slate-200">Local Area Network</h6>
                                        <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">Range: Building/Campus | Ethernet, WiFi</p>
                                        <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-1">Security: ARP spoofing, VLAN hopping, rogue APs</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex items-start space-x-4 p-4 bg-slate-800 rounded-lg">
                                    <div class="layer-indicator bg-green-600 text-white text-xs">MAN</div>
                                    <div>
                                        <h6 class="font-semibold text-slate-200">Metropolitan Area Network</h6>
                                        <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">Range: City | Metro Ethernet, MPLS</p>
                                        <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-1">Security: Provider security, last-mile interception</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex items-start space-x-4 p-4 bg-slate-800 rounded-lg">
                                    <div class="layer-indicator bg-orange-600 text-white text-xs">WAN</div>
                                    <div>
                                        <h6 class="font-semibold text-slate-200">Wide Area Network</h6>
                                        <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">Range: Global | Internet, leased lines, VPNs</p>
                                        <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-1">Security: BGP hijacking, DDoS, nation-state interception</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.1.2 Network Topologies & Security Implications</h4>

                        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                            Physical and logical topology determines failure modes, broadcast domains, and attack propagation paths.
                        </p>

                        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Physical Topologies</h5>
                                <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-slate-300">
                                    <li><strong>Bus:</strong> Single cable, collisions, hard to troubleshoot</li>
                                    <li><strong>Star:</strong> Central switch/hub, single point of failure, easy port security</li>
                                    <li><strong>Ring:</strong> Token passing, deterministic, complex failure recovery</li>
                                    <li><strong>Mesh:</strong> Redundant paths, expensive, complex routing</li>
                                    <li><strong>Tree:</strong> Hierarchical, scalable, root vulnerability</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Logical Topologies</h5>
                                <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-slate-300">
                                    <li><strong>Broadcast:</strong> Ethernet, WiFi - all nodes see all traffic (promiscuous mode)</li>
                                    <li><strong>Point-to-Point:</strong> PPP, T1 - dedicated link, easier to secure</li>
                                    <li><strong>Switched:</strong> Unicast forwarding, VLAN segmentation</li>
                                    <li><strong>Overlay:</strong> VPNs, SD-WAN - abstraction over physical</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.1.3 Transmission Media Deep Dive</h4>

