                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.2.1 Fundamental Concepts</h4>

                        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                            The Physical Layer is responsible for the transparent transmission of raw bit streams over a physical 
                            medium. It defines:
                        </p>

                        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Mechanical Specifications</h5>
                                <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-300">
                                    <li>• Connector types (RJ45, SFP, BNC, USB-C)</li>
                                    <li>• Pin assignments and layouts</li>
                                    <li>• Cable dimensions and tolerances</li>
                                    <li>• Maximum transmission distances</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Electrical/Optical Specifications</h5>
                                <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-300">
                                    <li>• Voltage levels (0/+5V, -3/+3V differential)</li>
                                    <li>• Impedance matching (100Ω for UTP)</li>
                                    <li>• Optical wavelengths (850nm, 1310nm, 1550nm)</li>
                                    <li>• Signal timing and jitter tolerances</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.2.2 Digital Signaling Deep Dive</h4>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">Non-Return-to-Zero (NRZ)</h5>
                            <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                                The simplest encoding: high voltage = 1, low voltage = 0. However, NRZ has critical limitations 
                                that make it unsuitable for modern networks:
                            </p>
                            <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-300 mb-4">
                                <li>• <strong>Baseline Wander:</strong> Long sequences of 1s or 0s cause DC drift</li>
                                <li>• <strong>Clock Recovery:</strong> No transitions means receiver loses synchronization</li>
                                <li>• <strong>Low Spectral Efficiency:</strong> Requires bandwidth equal to bit rate</li>
                            </ul>
                            <div class="bg-slate-800 p-4 rounded">
                                <p class="text-xs text-slate-400 mb-2">NRZ Encoding Example:</p>
                                <div class="flex items-center space-x-1 font-mono text-sm">
                                    <span class="text-blue-400">Data:</span>
                                    <span>1 1 0 1 0 0 1 0</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="mt-2 h-16 relative bg-slate-900 rounded overflow-hidden">
                                    <svg viewBox="0 0 400 60" class="w-full h-full">
                                        <line x1="0" y1="30" x2="400" y2="30" stroke="#475569" stroke-width="1"/>
                                        <path d="M 0 10 L 100 10 L 100 50 L 150 50 L 150 10 L 200 10 L 200 50 L 300 50 L 300 10 L 350 10" 
                                              stroke="#3b82f6" stroke-width="3" fill="none"/>
                                    </svg>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">Manchester Encoding (IEEE 802.3)</h5>
                            <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                                Used in 10BASE-T Ethernet. Each bit period contains a transition: low-to-high = 0, high-to-low = 1.
                                Guarantees clock recovery but requires 2x bandwidth (20MHz for 10Mbps).
                            </p>
                            <div class="bg-slate-800 p-4 rounded">
                                <p class="text-xs text-slate-400 mb-2">Manchester Encoding:</p>
                                <div class="flex items-center space-x-1 font-mono text-sm mb-2">
                                    <span class="text-blue-400">Data:</span>
                                    <span>0 1</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="text-xs text-slate-500 space-y-1">
                                    <p>0 = Low-to-High transition (↓↑)</p>
                                    <p>1 = High-to-Low transition (↑↓)</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">4B/5B and 8B/10B Encoding</h5>
                            <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                                Modern Ethernet uses block coding to ensure sufficient transitions for clock recovery while 
                                maintaining DC balance:
                            </p>
                            <div class="space-y-3">
                                <div class="bg-slate-800 p-3 rounded">
                                    <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-400">4B/5B (100BASE-X)</p>
                                    <p class="text-xs text-slate-400">Maps 4 data bits to 5 code bits. 16 data patterns + 16 control patterns. 
                                    80% efficiency, guarantees max 3 consecutive 0s.</p>
                                </div>
                                <div class="bg-slate-800 p-3 rounded">
                                    <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-400">8B/10B (Gigabit Ethernet)</p>
                                    <p class="text-xs text-slate-400">Maps 8 bits to 10 bits. 256 data + 12 control codes (K-codes). 
                                    Maintains DC balance, limited run length, error detection.</p>
                                </div>
                                <div class="bg-slate-800 p-3 rounded">
