                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 border-red-500/30">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-red-400 mb-3">TEMPEST Attacks</h5>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 mb-3">
                                    Electromagnetic emanations from network cables and devices can be intercepted and analyzed 
                                    to reconstruct data. CRT monitors were particularly vulnerable; modern LCDs emit less but 
                                    cables remain vulnerable.
                                </p>
                                <ul class="text-xs text-slate-400 space-y-1">
                                    <li>• Shielded cables (STP, SCTP) reduce emissions</li>
                                    <li>• Faraday cages for high-security environments</li>
                                    <li>• Distance: signal strength follows inverse-square law</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 border-red-500/30">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-red-400 mb-3">Physical Tap Detection</h5>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 mb-3">
                                    Unauthorized physical connections can be detected through:
                                </p>
                                <ul class="text-xs text-slate-400 space-y-1">
                                    <li>• Time Domain Reflectometry (TDR) - measures impedance changes</li>
                                    <li>• Optical Time Domain Reflectometer (OTDR) for fiber</li>
                                    <li>• Power monitoring (insertion loss)</li>
                                    <li>• Port security (MAC address limiting)</li>
                                </ul>
