                            <h3 class="text-3xl font-bold serif text-white">OSI Layer 2: Data Link Layer</h3>
                            <p class="text-blue-400">Frames, MAC Addresses, and Local Delivery</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none">
                        <div class="highlight-box rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-300">Infinite Depth Analysis</h4>
                            <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                                The Data Link Layer provides node-to-node delivery, transforming the error-prone physical layer 
                                into a reliable link. This is where MAC addresses, Ethernet frames, switches, and VLANs operate. 
                                Understanding Layer 2 is critical for network segmentation, ARP security, and switch infrastructure 
                                protection.
                            </p>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.3.1 Data Link Layer Functions</h4>

                        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Framing</h5>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 mb-3">
                                    Encapsulating network layer packets into frames with headers and trailers that define 
                                    boundaries and addressing.
                                </p>
                                <ul class="text-xs text-slate-400 space-y-1">
                                    <li>• Frame delimitation (start/end markers)</li>
                                    <li>• Addressing (source/destination MAC)</li>
                                    <li>• Type/Length identification</li>
                                    <li>• Payload encapsulation</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Error Detection</h5>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 mb-3">
                                    Detecting transmission errors through checksums. Note: Layer 2 detects but does not correct 
                                    errors (no retransmission at this layer).
                                </p>
                                <ul class="text-xs text-slate-400 space-y-1">
                                    <li>• Cyclic Redundancy Check (CRC-32 in Ethernet)</li>
                                    <li>• Frame Check Sequence (FCS)</li>
                                    <li>• Discard corrupted frames</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.3.2 Ethernet Frame Structure (Infinite Detail)</h4>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">Ethernet II Frame Format (DIX)</h5>
                            <div class="overflow-x-auto">
                                <div class="min-w-max">
                                    <div class="flex text-xs text-center">
                                        <div class="w-24 p-2 bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/30">
                                            <div class="font-semibold text-purple-300">Preamble</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-400">7 bytes</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-500">10101010...</div>
                                        </div>
                                        <div class="w-16 p-2 bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/30">
                                            <div class="font-semibold text-purple-300">SFD</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-400">1 byte</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-500">10101011</div>
                                        </div>
                                        <div class="w-32 p-2 bg-blue-900/50 border border-blue-500/30">
                                            <div class="font-semibold text-blue-300">Destination MAC</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-400">6 bytes</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-500">Unicast/Multicast/Broadcast</div>
                                        </div>
                                        <div class="w-32 p-2 bg-blue-900/50 border border-blue-500/30">
                                            <div class="font-semibold text-blue-300">Source MAC</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-400">6 bytes</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-500">OUI + NIC specific</div>
                                        </div>
                                        <div class="w-24 p-2 bg-green-900/50 border border-green-500/30">
                                            <div class="font-semibold text-green-300">Type</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-400">2 bytes</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-500">0x0800=IPv4</div>
                                        </div>
                                        <div class="w-64 p-2 bg-slate-800 border border-slate-600">
                                            <div class="font-semibold text-slate-300">Payload</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-400">46-1500 bytes</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-500">LLC data + Pad</div>
                                        </div>
                                        <div class="w-24 p-2 bg-red-900/50 border border-red-500/30">
                                            <div class="font-semibold text-red-300">FCS</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-400">4 bytes</div>
                                            <div class="text-slate-500">CRC-32</div>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <p class="text-xs text-slate-400 mt-4">
                                Minimum frame size: 64 bytes (excluding preamble/SFD). Maximum: 1518 bytes (1522 with VLAN tag).
                                Jumbo frames: up to 9000 bytes (non-standard).
                            </p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">MAC Address Structure</h5>
                            <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4 text-sm">
                                Media Access Control addresses are 48-bit identifiers burned into NICs (though often spoofable in software).
                            </p>
                            <div class="bg-slate-800 p-4 rounded font-mono text-sm">
                                <div class="flex items-center space-x-2 mb-2">
                                    <span class="text-blue-400">XX</span>
                                    <span class="text-slate-500">:</span>
                                    <span class="text-blue-400">XX</span>
                                    <span class="text-slate-500">:</span>
                                    <span class="text-blue-400">XX</span>
                                    <span class="text-slate-500">:</span>
                                    <span class="text-green-400">YY</span>
                                    <span class="text-slate-500">:</span>
                                    <span class="text-green-400">YY</span>
                                    <span class="text-slate-500">:</span>
                                    <span class="text-green-400">YY</span>
                                </div>
                                <div class="text-xs space-y-1 text-slate-400">
                                    <p><span class="text-blue-400">XX:XX:XX</span> = OUI (Organizationally Unique Identifier) - IEEE assigned</p>
                                    <p><span class="text-green-400">YY:YY:YY</span> = NIC specific - Manufacturer assigned</p>
                                    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-500">First byte least significant bits:</p>
                                    <p>• Bit 0: 0=Unicast, 1=Multicast</p>
                                    <p>• Bit 1: 0=Global (UAA), 1=Local (LAA)</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.3.3 Media Access Control</h4>

                        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                            Controlling access to shared media prevents collisions in half-duplex environments. Modern switched 
                            networks operate in full-duplex, eliminating the need for CSMA/CD.
                        </p>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">CSMA/CD (Carrier Sense Multiple Access with Collision Detection)</h5>
                            <p class="text-slate-300 text-sm mb-4">
                                Used in legacy half-duplex Ethernet:
                            </p>
                            <ol class="list-decimal list-inside text-sm text-slate-300 space-y-2 ml-4">
                                <li><strong>Carrier Sense:</strong> Listen before transmitting. If medium idle, transmit.</li>
                                <li><strong>Collision Detection:</strong> Monitor while transmitting. If collision detected (voltage spike), stop.</li>
                                <li><strong>Jam Signal:</strong> Transmit 32-bit jam to ensure all stations detect collision.</li>
                                <li><strong>Backoff:</strong> Wait random time (truncated binary exponential backoff: 0 to 2ⁿ-1 slot times).</li>
                                <li><strong>Retry:</strong> Attempt retransmission (max 16 attempts).</li>
                            </ol>
                            <p class="text-slate-400 text-xs mt-4">
                                <strong>Slot time:</strong> 512 bit times (51.2μs at 10Mbps). Ensures collision detection even at maximum 
                                network diameter. Minimum frame size (64 bytes) ensures transmission lasts at least one slot time.
                            </p>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.3.4 Switches & MAC Address Tables</h4>

                        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                            Switches operate at Layer 2, forwarding frames based on MAC addresses. They learn source addresses 
                            and forward to known destinations or flood unknown destinations.
                        </p>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">Switch Operation Modes</h5>
                            <div class="space-y-4">
                                <div class="bg-slate-800 p-4 rounded">
                                    <h6 class="font-semibold text-green-400 mb-2">Store-and-Forward</h6>
                                    <p class="text-sm text-slate-300">Receive entire frame, verify FCS, then forward. 
                                    Latency = frame size + processing. No error propagation.</p>
                                </div>
                                <div class="bg-slate-800 p-4 rounded">
                                    <h6 class="font-semibold text-yellow-400 mb-2">Cut-Through</h6>
                                    <p class="text-sm text-slate-300">Forward after reading destination MAC (first 14 bytes). 
                                    Low latency but forwards corrupted frames.</p>
                                </div>
                                <div class="bg-slate-800 p-4 rounded">
                                    <h6 class="font-semibold text-orange-400 mb-2">Fragment-Free</h6>
                                    <p class="text-sm text-slate-300">Forward after first 64 bytes (minimum valid frame size). 
                                    Compromise between speed and error checking.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.3.5 VLANs (Virtual LANs)</h4>

                        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                            VLANs provide logical segmentation at Layer 2, creating separate broadcast domains without physical 
                            separation. Critical for network security and traffic isolation.
                        </p>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">802.1Q VLAN Tagging</h5>
                            <p class="text-slate-300 text-sm mb-4">
                                4-byte tag inserted after source MAC address:
                            </p>
                            <div class="bg-slate-800 p-4 rounded font-mono text-xs">
                                <div class="grid grid-cols-4 gap-2 text-center">
                                    <div class="p-2 border border-slate-600 rounded">
                                        <div class="text-blue-400">TPID</div>
                                        <div class="text-slate-500">16 bits</div>
                                        <div class="text-slate-600">0x8100</div>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="p-2 border border-slate-600 rounded">
                                        <div class="text-blue-400">PCP</div>
                                        <div class="text-slate-500">3 bits</div>
                                        <div class="text-slate-600">Priority</div>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="p-2 border border-slate-600 rounded">
                                        <div class="text-blue-400">DEI</div>
                                        <div class="text-slate-500">1 bit</div>
                                        <div class="text-slate-600">Drop eligible</div>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="p-2 border border-slate-600 rounded">
                                        <div class="text-blue-400">VID</div>
                                        <div class="text-slate-500">12 bits</div>
                                        <div class="text-slate-600">VLAN ID (1-4094)</div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <p class="text-slate-400 text-xs mt-4">
                                Native VLAN: Untagged traffic on a trunk. Must match between switches or VLAN hopping occurs.
                                VLAN 1 is default/native; best practice is to change it and prune unused VLANs.
                            </p>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.3.6 ARP (Address Resolution Protocol)</h4>

                        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                            ARP maps Layer 3 IP addresses to Layer 2 MAC addresses. It is stateless and unauthenticated, 
                            making it vulnerable to spoofing attacks.
                        </p>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">ARP Operation</h5>
                            <div class="space-y-3 text-sm">
                                <div class="flex items-center space-x-4 p-3 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <div class="w-8 h-8 bg-blue-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold">1</div>
                                    <div>
                                        <p class="text-slate-200">Host A needs MAC of 192.168.1.5</p>
                                        <p class="text-slate-400 text-xs">Checks ARP cache first</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex items-center space-x-4 p-3 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <div class="w-8 h-8 bg-blue-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold">2</div>
                                    <div>
                                        <p class="text-slate-200">Broadcasts ARP Request</p>
                                        <p class="text-slate-400 text-xs">Dst MAC: FF:FF:FF:FF:FF:FF | "Who has 192.168.1.5?"</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex items-center space-x-4 p-3 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <div class="w-8 h-8 bg-blue-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold">3</div>
                                    <div>
                                        <p class="text-slate-200">Host B (192.168.1.5) responds</p>
                                        <p class="text-slate-400 text-xs">Unicast ARP Reply: "192.168.1.5 is at MAC_B"</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex items-center space-x-4 p-3 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                    <div class="w-8 h-8 bg-blue-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold">4</div>
                                    <div>
                                        <p class="text-slate-200">Host A caches mapping</p>
                                        <p class="text-slate-400 text-xs">Entry expires typically after 4-20 minutes</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 border-red-500/30">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-red-400 mb-3">ARP Spoofing Attack</h5>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 mb-3">
                                    Attacker sends gratuitous ARP replies poisoning targets' caches:
                                </p>
                                <ul class="text-xs text-slate-400 space-y-1">
                                    <li>• Tell victim: "Gateway IP is at Attacker_MAC"</li>
                                    <li>• Tell gateway: "Victim IP is at Attacker_MAC"</li>
                                    <li>• Attacker becomes man-in-the-middle</li>
                                    <li>• Enable IP forwarding to maintain connectivity</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 border-green-500/30">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-green-400 mb-3">ARP Security Measures</h5>
                                <ul class="text-sm text-slate-300 space-y-2">
                                    <li>• <strong>Static ARP entries:</strong> Bind critical IPs to MACs</li>
                                    <li>• <strong>ARP inspection:</strong> Switch validates ARP packets</li>
                                    <li>• <strong>Dynamic ARP Inspection (DAI):</strong> Uses DHCP snooping database</li>
                                    <li>• <strong>Private VLANs:</strong> Prevent inter-host communication</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="highlight-box rounded-xl p-6 mt-8">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-300">Practical Lab: Layer 2 Analysis</h4>
                            <div class="code-block p-4 rounded space-y-2">
                                <p class="text-slate-400"># View ARP cache</p>
                                <p class="text-green-400">$ arp -a</p>
                                <p class="text-green-400">$ ip neigh</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-400 mt-2"># Capture and analyze ARP traffic</p>
                                <p class="text-green-400">$ tcpdump -i eth0 arp -n</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-400 mt-2"># Perform ARP spoofing (testing only!)</p>
                                <p class="text-green-400">$ arpspoof -i eth0 -t 192.168.1.1 192.168.1.100</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-400 mt-2"># View MAC address table on Linux bridge</p>
                                <p class="text-green-400">$ brctl showmacs br0</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-400 mt-2"># Check VLAN configuration</p>
                                <p class="text-green-400">$ cat /proc/net/vlan/config</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
