                    <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none">
                        <div class="highlight-box rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-300">Infinite Depth Analysis</h4>
                            <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed">
                                The Network Layer enables internetworking—communication across different physical networks. 
                                This is where IP addressing, routing algorithms, and packet forwarding operate. Understanding 
                                Layer 3 is essential for network design, troubleshooting, and securing traffic flow across 
                                autonomous systems.
                            </p>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.4.1 Internet Protocol (IP) Fundamentals</h4>

                        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                            IP provides logical addressing and best-effort delivery. It is connectionless (no setup) and 
                            unreliable (no guarantees), leaving reliability to upper layers (TCP) or applications.
                        </p>

                        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">IPv4 Header Structure (20-60 bytes)</h5>
                                <div class="space-y-2 text-xs font-mono">
                                    <div class="flex justify-between p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                        <span class="text-slate-400">Version (4)</span>
                                        <span class="text-blue-400">IHL (4)</span>
                                        <span class="text-green-400">TOS (8)</span>
                                        <span class="text-yellow-400">Total Length (16)</span>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="flex justify-between p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                        <span class="text-purple-400">Identification (16)</span>
                                        <span class="text-orange-400">Flags (3)</span>
                                        <span class="text-red-400">Fragment Offset (13)</span>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="flex justify-between p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded">
                                        <span class="text-blue-400">TTL (8)</span>
                                        <span class="text-green-400">Protocol (8)</span>
                                        <span class="text-yellow-400">Header Checksum (16)</span>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded text-center text-blue-400">Source IP Address (32)</div>
                                    <div class="p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded text-center text-green-400">Destination IP Address (32)</div>
                                    <div class="p-2 bg-slate-800 rounded text-center text-slate-500">Options + Padding (0-40)</div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Critical Header Fields</h5>
                                <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-300">
                                    <li><strong>TTL (Time To Live):</strong> Decremented at each hop. Prevents routing loops. Used in traceroute.</li>
                                    <li><strong>Protocol:</strong> Identifies payload type (6=TCP, 17=UDP, 1=ICMP, 50=ESP)</li>
                                    <li><strong>Fragmentation:</strong> Identification, Flags (DF, MF), Offset for reassembly</li>
                                    <li><strong>TOS/DSCP:</strong> Quality of Service marking</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.4.2 IP Addressing & Subnetting Mastery</h4>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">IPv4 Address Classes (Historical)</h5>
                            <div class="overflow-x-auto">
                                <table class="w-full text-xs text-left text-slate-300">
                                    <thead class="text-slate-400 uppercase bg-slate-800">
                                        <tr>
                                            <th class="px-3 py-2">Class</th>
                                            <th class="px-3 py-2">First Bits</th>
                                            <th class="px-3 py-2">Range</th>
                                            <th class="px-3 py-2">Default Mask</th>
                                            <th class="px-3 py-2">Networks/Hosts</th>
                                        </tr>
                                    </thead>
                                    <tbody class="divide-y divide-slate-700">
                                        <tr class="bg-slate-900/50">
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2 font-semibold">A</td>
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2">0</td>
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2">1.0.0.0 - 126.0.0.0</td>
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2">/8 (255.0.0.0)</td>
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2">128 nets / 16M hosts</td>
                                        </tr>
                                        <tr>
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2 font-semibold">B</td>
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2">10</td>
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2">128.0.0.0 - 191.255.0.0</td>
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2">/16 (255.255.0.0)</td>
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2">16K nets / 65K hosts</td>
                                        </tr>
                                        <tr class="bg-slate-900/50">
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2 font-semibold">C</td>
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2">110</td>
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2">192.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.0</td>
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2">/24 (255.255.255.0)</td>
                                            <td class="px-3 py-2">2M nets / 254 hosts</td>
                                        </tr>
                                    </tbody>
                                </table>
                            </div>
                            <p class="text-xs text-slate-400 mt-2">
                                Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) replaced classes in 1993, allowing arbitrary prefix lengths.
                            </p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">CIDR and VLSM (Variable Length Subnet Masking)</h5>
                            <p class="text-slate-300 text-sm mb-4">
                                CIDR notation (e.g., 192.168.1.0/24) specifies the network prefix length, enabling flexible 
                                allocation and route aggregation (supernetting).
                            </p>
                            <div class="grid grid-cols-4 gap-2 text-xs">
                                <div class="bg-slate-800 p-2 rounded text-center">
                                    <div class="text-blue-400 font-bold">/30</div>
                                    <div class="text-slate-400">255.255.255.252</div>
                                    <div class="text-slate-500">2 hosts</div>
                                    <div class="text-slate-600">Point-to-point</div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="bg-slate-800 p-2 rounded text-center">
                                    <div class="text-blue-400 font-bold">/29</div>
                                    <div class="text-slate-400">255.255.255.248</div>
                                    <div class="text-slate-500">6 hosts</div>
                                    <div class="text-slate-600">Small subnets</div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="bg-slate-800 p-2 rounded text-center">
                                    <div class="text-blue-400 font-bold">/24</div>
                                    <div class="text-slate-400">255.255.255.0</div>
                                    <div class="text-slate-500">254 hosts</div>
                                    <div class="text-slate-600">Class C replacement</div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="bg-slate-800 p-2 rounded text-center">
                                    <div class="text-blue-400 font-bold">/16</div>
                                    <div class="text-slate-400">255.255.0.0</div>
                                    <div class="text-slate-500">65,534 hosts</div>
                                    <div class="text-slate-600">Large organizations</div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">Subnetting Calculations</h5>
                            <p class="text-slate-300 text-sm mb-4">
                                Given network 172.16.0.0/16, create subnets for 4 departments with ~1000 hosts each:
                            </p>
                            <div class="code-block p-4 rounded text-sm">
                                <p class="text-slate-400">Requirements: 1000 hosts per subnet</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-400">Hosts needed: 1000 → requires 10 bits (2^10 = 1024)</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-400">Network bits: 32 - 10 = 22</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-400">New mask: /22 (255.255.252.0)</p>
                                <p class="text-blue-400 mt-2">Subnet 1: 172.16.0.0/22 (0.1 - 3.254)</p>
                                <p class="text-green-400">Subnet 2: 172.16.4.0/22 (4.1 - 7.254)</p>
                                <p class="text-yellow-400">Subnet 3: 172.16.8.0/22 (8.1 - 11.254)</p>
                                <p class="text-purple-400">Subnet 4: 172.16.12.0/22 (12.1 - 15.254)</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-500 mt-2">Block size: 4 (256 - 252 = 4)</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.4.3 IPv6: The Next Generation</h4>

                        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                            IPv6 addresses 32-bit exhaustion with 128-bit addresses (3.4×10³⁸ total), simplified headers, 
                            and built-in security features.
                        </p>

                        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">IPv6 Address Format</h5>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 mb-3">
                                    128 bits = 8 groups of 4 hex digits, colon-separated:
                                </p>
                                <div class="bg-slate-800 p-3 rounded font-mono text-xs">
                                    <p class="text-green-400">Full: 2001:0db8:85a3:0000:0000:8a2e:0370:7334</p>
                                    <p class="text-blue-400 mt-2">Compressed: 2001:db8:85a3::8a2e:370:7334</p>
                                    <p class="text-slate-500 mt-2">:: replaces one group of consecutive zeros</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">IPv6 Address Types</h5>
                                <ul class="space-y-2 text-xs text-slate-300">
                                    <li><strong>Unicast:</strong> One-to-one (Global, Link-local, Unique-local)</li>
                                    <li><strong>Multicast:</strong> One-to-many (FF00::/8)</li>
                                    <li><strong>Anycast:</strong> One-to-nearest (same address on multiple nodes)</li>
                                    <li><strong>Loopback:</strong> ::1</li>
                                    <li><strong>Unspecified:</strong> ::</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-blue-300 mt-8 mb-4">2.4.4 Routing Fundamentals</h4>

                        <p class="text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                            Routing determines the path packets take across networks. Routers maintain routing tables and 
                            forward packets based on destination IP addresses.
                        </p>

                        <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
                            <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-4">Routing Table Components</h5>
                            <div class="code-block p-4 rounded text-sm">
                                <p class="text-slate-400">$ ip route</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-300 mt-2">default via 192.168.1.1 dev eth0 proto dhcp metric 100</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-300">10.0.0.0/8 via 10.0.0.1 dev eth1</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-300">192.168.1.0/24 dev eth0 proto kernel scope link src 192.168.1.100</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-500 mt-2"># Components:</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-500"># Destination (prefix/mask)</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-500"># Next-hop (gateway)</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-500"># Outgoing interface</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-500"># Metric (cost/distance)</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-500"># Administrative Distance (trustworthiness)</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Static Routing</h5>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 mb-3">
                                    Manually configured routes. Best for small networks or specific security requirements.
                                </p>
                                <ul class="text-xs text-slate-400 space-y-1">
                                    <li>• Pros: Predictable, no overhead, secure</li>
                                    <li>• Cons: Not scalable, manual failover</li>
                                    <li>• Use case: Default routes, stub networks</li>
                                    <li>• AD: 1 (most trusted)</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                            <div class="detail-box rounded-lg p-6">
                                <h5 class="font-semibold text-blue-300 mb-3">Dynamic Routing</h5>
                                <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 mb-3">
                                    Routers exchange information to adapt to topology changes automatically.
                                </p>
                                <ul class="text-xs text-slate-400 space-y-1">
                                    <li>• IGP (Interior): RIP, OSPF, EIGRP, IS-IS</li>
                                    <li>• EGP (Exterior): BGP (inter-AS routing)</li>
                                    <li>• Distance Vector vs. Link State</li>
                                    <li>• Convergence time critical for security</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="highlight-box rounded-xl p-6 mt-8">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-blue-300">Practical Lab: Layer 3 Operations</h4>
                            <div class="code-block p-4 rounded space-y-2">
                                <p class="text-slate-400"># View routing table</p>
                                <p class="text-green-400">$ ip route show</p>
                                <p class="text-green-400">$ route -n</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-400 mt-2"># Trace route path</p>
                                <p class="text-green-400">$ traceroute 8.8.8.8</p>
                                <p class="text-green-400">$ mtr 8.8.8.8</p>
                                <p class="text-slate-400 mt-2"># Capture ICMP for routing analysis</p>
